// ── BRIDGE PARTS — for two-clause body sentences ───────────────────────────
//
// Per-food short phrases used as the SUBJECT of body-bridge clauses. The
// goal: produce sentences like
//
//    "the lean cut handles the parmesan-and-truffle weight, and the buttery
//     beef frames the savory umami depth."
//
// where the two clauses each pull a different "subject" + "target" pair.
// Each food gets:
//   subjects: 2 short noun phrases describing what the food brings to a
//             bridge clause (its texture/cut/structure side AND its flavor
//             side).
//   targets:  2 short noun phrases for what the food looks like as the
//             OBJECT of a bridge -- "the parmesan-and-truffle weight",
//             "the savory umami depth", "the rich greens".
//
// Where a food doesn't have an explicit entry, we fall back to character +
// short name; less specific but readable.

